:: Islington_traditions-cap [nobr]

<<timed 00s>>
  <<replace "#caption">>  
One of the traditions that they have in Islington, 
<</replace>>
<</timed>>

<<timed 04s>>
  <<replace "#caption">>  
well, two, one is beating the bounds, which I believe they do every year. 
<</replace>>
<</timed>>

<<timed 09s>>
  <<replace "#caption">>  
You go around the perimeter of the borough and you do something smack on the gate of whatever it is, or 
<</replace>>
<</timed>>

<<timed 17s>>
  <<replace "#caption">>  
hit the milestone at the border of the borough, and you just walk around. 
<</replace>>
<</timed>>

<<timed 25s>>
  <<replace "#caption">>  
I think it's about a 5-10 mile walk, and when you're finished, you've beaten the bounds. 
<</replace>>
<</timed>>

<<timed 29s>>
  <<replace "#caption">>  
The other thing that's a lot more fun is when we have a new Mayor every May, because the mayorship revolves around the councilors. 
<</replace>>
<</timed>>

<<timed 38.5s>>
  <<replace "#caption">>  
That mayor will come out in their full regalia, gold chains and red cloak, and talk to people in various community events that might be happening, 
<</replace>>
<</timed>>

<<timed 49.5s>>
  <<replace "#caption">>  
just to introduce him or herself to the rest of us. 
<</replace>>
<</timed>>

<<timed 55s>>
  <<replace "#caption">>  
That's quite old-fashioned in many ways, but they managed to keep up to date because they talk about things that we're interested in, 
<</replace>>
<</timed>>

<<timed 60s>>
  <<replace "#caption">>  
like housing or violence against women and girls, the issues that of the day, 
<</replace>>
<</timed>>

<<timed 66.5s>>
  <<replace "#caption">>  
which are important to people in the area. 
<</replace>>
<</timed>>

<<timed 69s>>
  <<replace "#caption">>  
So, yes, it's sort of a combination of old-fashioned wearing the gold regalia, 
<</replace>>
<</timed>>

<<timed 74.5s>>
  <<replace "#caption">>  
which probably wouldn't be made these days, 
<</replace>>
<</timed>>

<<timed 77s>>
  <<replace "#caption">>  
and the red cloak, and talking about modern issues that mean a lot to us, 
<</replace>>
<</timed>>

<<timed 80.5s>>
  <<replace "#caption">>  
and just coming out and patting kids on the head 
<</replace>>
<</timed>>

<<timed 83.5s>>
  <<replace "#caption">>  
like people used to do.
<</replace>>
<</timed>>



